values:
Dear Shinedown, 

Thank you for letting me pay you for your therapy session and ruining your music for me forever. I will now think of little kids losing their mommies (which was not even real but a dream you had about a fake person!) and your buddy's cousin almost commiting suicide on Christmas when I hear your songs, instead of getting lost in the sounds and enjoying myself. 

I was lured in with the promise of an acoustic set. 
I paid more than I wanted to, but acoustic music always relaxes me and puts me in a good mood. So I thought, eh its only money. 
I had a terrible day - tests and papers due dates changed for the millionth time this week, and more assignments piled on. A useless 2 hour last minute group meeting that could have waited until March. 
Went to dinner with the hubby and drank two beers, getting excited for the acoustic, starting to feel better.....
Got a happy little buzz going on....
enjoying the masonic temple's smooth granite walls and bubbly imperfections
Melting into my chair for the first guys last two songs, loving the gutair
2nd band, buzz is fading - realizing the rest of the concert is "full band acoustic" and was going to be a lot louder than anticipated
After a 1/2 hour set change shindown opens with beautiful gutair I am loving it. 
Then before every song leadman needs to talk for 10 minutes about himself, why he wrote the song, I was a drug addict, not I am not. I was vain, now I am not. (Still vain I think)
And it keeps going before every song......
So now do I light my CDs on fire? I'll never forget the stories. 
I remember years ago when i found out a fuel song i liked was written about the singer's grandma who had cancer and did not tell him
now i think of that every time i hear it
then I think about my grandma getting cancer. I can forgive the fuel guy though - it was the radio you can change it if you do not want to know and he was only talking about 1 song. 

Literally every song. 
I had to leave. 

I am angry.

Weekends go by too fast, if you can call them weekends, lol. I thought this one wouldn't be too bad since I do not have tests until Thursday and Friday. I figured study a little for both and finish my MD applications (10 submitted, 4 left). But then on Thursday, a teacher decided to assign a group project paper due Monday. Spent Friday night searching the good ole research databases and Saturday morning meeting with a group that someone did not think they had to come to because they were hungover.

Then hell, a girl's got to have some fun and my class had organized an outing to Roba's farm and pumkin patch, so I took Rob, Becky and Jeremy. We dipped our cider donuts into apple cider, giggled at obese rabbits, spent an hour in the ginormous corn maze (sans map), shot pumpkins out of cannons, got some pumpkins and had a good time. I hit the metal cows 4 out of 5 times with my pumpkins! Afterwards Rob wanted to go to the movies with his buddies so we went to see Let me in. It's about vampires - interesting story line. a little girl vampire makes friends with lonely, little human boys, so they grow up and help her get food until they are old and die and the next lonely little boy comes along Was a little slow at times, but overall I liked it. Came home worked on the group paper a little, then headed to bed.
 
I remember on the way to the movies, there was a cool suset. A thin ribbon of orange above the hills.....

Now it is 7pm and pitch black - o long summer days I miss you.

Today I have been having software issues with the program I was going to use to help me study. So I studied one subject a bit, but not the way I intended and right now I am procrastinating the other one. I also think I finished up two secondary apps. I've sent them off to be reviewed. I am trying to prepare myself for being sick (I am very bad at it). It may be inevitable because Rob is sick and my mother is law too. 
I also have an insatiable need for chocolate today. I've eaten 3 mini baby ruths, two dark chocolate covered pretzels, and a scratch made brownie. Still I want more!

I have been thinking about livejournal for a while. Wanting to write, not wanting to write. Wanting people to know my thoughts but then not wanting them to. I simultaneously wish all of my friends in the world, my true friends the ones that know me, would read this, but then part of me would feel embarrassed if they did. 

I'm a mess again. I'm depressed. I realized it a few days ago. Yesterday I cried and was a fool to think that the depression escaped with my tears. 

A lot of people just think it's from school. Someone told me yesterday, med school is just going to be worse you know. (O yea I did not get in this year by the way; I do not count wait-lists.) Well, yes med school is going to be worse than the master's program I am in now BUT this is not about having a boatload of work to do, a test, sometimes two every week, and no freetime. Ok well it probably contributes.

I've just had one hell of a year. I want 2010 to be over. Let's recap: dead father and all the trappings that come with that including motherly guilt trips, quite a few medical school rejections, grandparents in trouble, uncle that has been in the ICU for 9 weeks on a rollercoaster of life and death, an MCAT disappointment, and a rigorous 1 year masters of science program that does not allow me to deal with all of this because there is no time, so I stuff it into my Kristina bag until I explode. 

I guess in that regards it is good I did not get into med school last year = even more stress and even less time to cope. Maybe I could have deferred and hung out and been groovy. I am kicking butt in the MBS program though, straight As so far. (too bad it is putting me another 40 grand in the hole) Plus I have an interview at George Washington University's medical school in December. 

I remember in middle/high school, I thought I felt nothing. I believed that I thought too much and did not feel enough. So I clung so the words of Eddie Vedder - "I don't want to think, I want to feel." And I tried to actively feel more.   Now I believe I am too emotional. A lot of the time I cannot hide my emotions - I cannot keep them from welling up inside of me. They show on my face, in my eyes.  So what do I do now?

This wonderful woman at school recommends breathing/meditation tapes and/or crying everyday. She says I need to let it out. Even when I let it out, it never feels like it goes away. It seems like that stuff only works when I am doing it, but then I am right back to square one when I'm finished.  So.....what?

Another issue I am struggling with is my "friends". A lot of them have not really talked to me since my dad passed. I am kinda pissed about this. However, do I have the right to be pissed?  I mean, if he did not die it is possible that with school and such I would not really have talked to them either. Yet, on the flip-side shouldn't they be checking to see how I am doing? Aren't I important enough?
Over the almost year of neglect I many times I have thought about writing in here....well now I can't sleep, and if I do not write it here I will end up writing it somewhere I regret.

Well, its obvious that I have not been using LJ as a procrastination tool to studying....so what have I been using lol.  6 weeks until the test. I studied all day yesterday but not at all today (spent too much time researching GPSs). So tomorrow I have to go into lockdown. I thought it being cold and dreary would make it easier to study, but it hasn't. Still I do not think I want to to be warm and sunny.

Melissa's birthday over two months ago was fun, just a simple beer to go with a band.  I got some funny pics.

2/14/2009 I let Rob hang with the boys, and I showed up later and tried roleplaying (Deadlands). Now I am pretty positive it is not for me, lol.  In its defense, I was bored because I did not get to do much. (I was rolling too low.) Though honestly, I prefer to be outside.

2/15/2009 I hung out with my Uncle Joe. We went for Chinese buffet right when they opened - talk about fresh. Then, we tried to assemble a bowflex that has been sitting in my mom's basement for at least a year. After 3 1/2 hours and 7 boxes we were almost done but could not find two very important bolts. We did not have anything big enough to subsitute with and are still waiting for mom to go to home depot and buy the needed bolts. Let me warn you potential bowflex customers, some assembly required is an understatement. Also make sure you measure the ceiling height beforehand. Ours almost did not fit - it just clears the ceiling.

2/16/2009 Rob and I had our V-day today after I went to the Sacred Heart Hospice Orientation. We went to Blue Wasabi for dinner, which had the best sushi we have ever tasted. Rob says even better than NY or DC. The expense is worth it.

2/21 Had dinner at Mom's

2/22 After Church and the gym went to see Taken with the parents in law. Good times.

2/27 Went for dinner at the Olive garden with friends from high school Jen and Christie. Catching up can be nice, but sometimes things do not need to be revived.
Later Becky, Jeremy, mom, and me went to the Woodlands. Becky wanted to dance, so we brought mom because I hate to dance. She loves it. We drank crazy girl drinks, yes I danced. And we got mom a date. She went on the date two days later, but the guy ended up being a douche who did not call her ever again because she wouldn't get physcial with him. I thought something was weird about a guy that goes tot he club without any friends.

March was a good month visited grandma a few times, took her to church some, went to the gym a lot (lost 10lbs), went to movies with candace, happy hours with Larae, made dinner at Beck and Jer's (Rob and I made our chipotle chicken tacos), had dinner at mom's, lunch with Aunt May and mom in law, worked every weekend, and hung out with people.  I learned at work that if the person working the shift after me calls off it is mandatory for me to stay or else I get fired. Unexpected 16 hour shifts are fun! I also learned that if your insurance is expiring you should not go hav somethign checked out until you get new insurance because the new insurance declines you for an undiagnosed condition (did not get test results back before applied) and you can really screw yourself if things do not come back normal.
See the dentist told me my left thyroid seemed puffy and to have it checked. The physcian ordered blood work and an ultrasound. Bloodwork normal, untrasound not, so a scan where you ingest a radioactive pill and get pics taken was ordered, of which I was not getting the results back untilt the day my  insurance expired.  So if I ended up needing a biopsy or worse surgery to reomve cancer, that all would come out f my own pocket. Fun and stressful. BUT thankfully everything turned out OK. 

April passed by in a blink. Jeff (dad in law) taught me to make chocolate covered cherries - my favorite. I had dinners with Beck and Jer, my mom, larae (for her b-day), my cousin John (made him dinner for graduation), and my bro Tim (for his b-day). I did some more hanging out some of the more memorable days were at the springbrook waterfall with Candace and her boy Alex, dyeing easter eggs with Rob and my brothers (separately), shopping with Terri, and going up to the Finger Lakes NY with Larae and her boyfriends friends. Up at the lakes we went on an all day wine tour of at least 12 wineries. I did not get drunkl though I think my tolerance was too far raised from the 8 white russians the night before, and oh how the milk alcohol mixture wrecked my stomach.  I have some great pics from that too.
Rob and I also finally tried Quaker State's luch buffet, where you can get any of their 20 wingsEXCEPT Atomic, and all you can EAT. We tried all the hots under atomic and a few of the milds. Buckeye BBQ and LA Lickers are very good. Supercharges at 5x less than Atomic are preeeeety hot and required some celery eaten afterwards, so I do not know how I can handle an Atomic, but I just want to try 1.

May is going along ok, but remember I have to go into lock down mode tomorrow. SIGH. This test this test this test - is so much under my skin. I hate that it determines so much - I don't agree with it.  My b-day is in a week (going to have a bonfire) - 26 and feeling old on some days because I feel behind. Where did the last eight years go?  No use dwelling. Anywho, did some yoga with candace, ate at a absolutely fantastic Italian place - Ragnottci' s in Dunmore - with Rob, and Sunday Aunt May came up and we made tabouli, hashwei, and kibbeh on the grill. We made 35 patties which were gone Monday, lol. Arabic food is so darn delicious.

2-9 skipped the gym because I could barely walk right after working out for 6 of the 7 last days.  

2-10 studied a little, had an interview for volunteering at Hospice of the Sacred Heart.  They offer so may good programs, and for free. So, thus far I like them and oritentation is on Monday. Met Beck and Jer at the gym at 7:30.

2-11 Cooked dad dinner. Got homemade kiebalski from Kutsop's market, which I never had and is so much better than Hilshire farms!, and mom's and pop's pierogies.  It was damn good..  Watched some TV with him them went to the gym alone as Beck and Jer had church. 

2-12 Went to the movies with mom, then lunch at Panera bread - good but I think quite possible overrated, met Larae at Applebee's for a cold brew, then off to the gym again. 

I've been a busy little bee, so to speak, hehe. I'm happy that I have a solid gyn routine down, but I still need to get studying in.  Sigh. I was hoping to get up early today and do it, but Rob is sick, which kept both of us up nearly all night.  I don't think I am going to do much this weekend but study, besides Mel's b-day tonight.

I don't know why more young people do not join community groups.  I guess too many already have their set social groups, which kinda sucks for anyone moving to a new area.  I never seem to find people more my age when I join them.  This is not the biggest deal in the world; I just want to meet people my age who have the same interests not people 30, 40 years older.   I joined  hiking group on meetup.com, and I haven't gone on an official hike yet because its been too damn cold for me and I do not have the proper gear, but I met up with one guy to take a walk on the cpuntry roads along Beaver Pond.  He was a nice enough fella, but like I said a bit older than what I am looking for.  The walk was nice, 3.85 miles, even though we did not see any beaver's or otters. Did see one rabbit and had two dogs following us for a bit.  I also saw a barn built in 1898. I am drawn to barns for some reason. All in all it was nice to get out.

Lackawanna State Park hosted a "Winterfest" today, which allowed me to do three things I have never done before, YAY!
First I got to walk on/across a frozen lake.  There was a thin layer of snow on the ice, so things were not slippery at all. I bet it is more interesting when it's more slippery. I thought this felt just like walking on the ground.  A big crowd of people was out in the middle of the lake listening to the Ice rescue people talk.  They had drilled a hole in the ice for some demonstrations, which I did not see.  I went over to listen for a minute and was watching a cute little tot in a pink snowsuit make snow angels when I heard this big crack. Everyone near the hole backed up about two feet. I found this quite comical. The rescue people said there was nothing to worry about because the ice was 8-10 inches thick.  Telling Rob this later he asked what they would of done had everyone fallen in. 

Next I strapped on some snowshoes and traversed the park.  I had to trudge up this huge snow covered hill to get the shoes, which quite frankly sucked, but going back up the hill with the shoes on to return them was a breeze.  I  guess they made their point; It surely was easier to walk in snow with them on (need a few inches though), and hell, I enjoyed it.  (unfortunately, now I want to buy some)

Finally, a DCNR ranger taught me and two others how to work a GPS unit and use it for geocaching. I'm a little torn because I've always wanted to to anti-GPS (use maps for driving, and map and compass to navigate outside) but I have to say it was kinda cool. AND WAY TOO EASY, lol.  I think I might like that you can set waypoints if you are wandering around, then just follow them back if you get lost.  Maybe if my orienteering skills were better.....   Ah, technology.  However, I do think geocaching is a great way to get kids outside. They do not want to be without their little technological devices ever, so why not combine them with the outdoors.  Whatever it takes to get more kids into outdoor activities and get some exercise, I am for.

1/22 - Rob and I cooked our soft chipotle chicken tacos for Jeff and Terri (my in-laws). We toned the spiciness down a bit for them, and they   
            really loved them. It feels great to have people enjoy your favorite recipes.  

1/23 - Since Luke/Erin and I each won a ticket to Wise Crackers the previous week, me; Rob, Beck and Jer, Jer's brother Doug and fiancee Nancy, and Beck's friends Trista and Brad  and Erin went again.  The comics were 10 times more funny that the previous week, and everyone had a good time, especially me.  Becky won a free ticket for the following week. Wow are we one lucky group. 

1/24 - I somehow found my way from Dalton to Tunkhannock (30 min drive) to the old Dietrich theater for a presentation on local hikes.  The directions I got were a  little sparce on landmarks so I kept thinking I passed the fork I was supposed to take.  I pulled over at a gas station to confirm and somehow missed the main drag and took the long way around Lake Winola, whose scenery was well worth the detour. It's a small lake and was frozen over. I saw some people playing in the middle of it.  Once in Tunk. it was difficult to find parking, so I missed the first 10 minutes of the present., which I think was the most informative part as I watched slides of places the guy had been for the next 20 min. and sat through a question and answer for thr last 10.  It was not a total loss though because I got an extensive list of web links to hiking clubs and trials, plus I now know how to get to Tunk, lol. 
Today was also national Yoga day and Prana Yoga in Dunmore was giving free classes in Vinyasa style flow - flowing pose to pose. Beck and I went. I liked the studio it was peaceful and colorful. I both liked and hated the lack of mirrors in the yoga room as I hate looking at my body with this foreign weight on it, but at the same time I can not see if I am executing a pose correctly....  I know that with time I will be able to tell when something is incorrect in position, but until that comes naturally vision is the best correcter.  O well. I do want to go back once I have the cash. 

1/25 - Had dinner at Aunt Patty's and Uncle Jimmy's. Homemade soup - YUM! (corn chowder, italian wedding, and pea)  Things weren't as jovial as X-mas eve, because Amy's husband  had to go and be a major ballless, worthless prick by cheating on her. They are separating. I just do not understand. Sigh. And I am sure the kids do not either. Bigger Sigh. I wish there was something I could do to make Amy feel better. I wish I knew her better. 

1/26 Mom and I went to see The Unborn. not as scary as I thought it would be. Decent. 

1/27 Went to visit grandma. She sent me home with shepard's pie and deer meatloaf. 

1/30 Had an interview with St. Joe's Center, a great organization that has a multitude of services for persons with mental handicaps. It is only a part time position - 16 hours every two weeks (every other weekend), but I think it would be extremely rewarding (and a bit humbling). I am really starting to feel my passion for helping underrepresented populations.  Thank you Dr. R. for allowing me the opportunity to work with and really get to know persons with DS. When I was a kid I was very shy around persons with disabilities, but after spending time with them I know any fear and uneasiness was just plain silly. They are fun, happy, wonderful, and (despite what many think) they can teach you a lot. 

2-1 Grandma's b-day and Superbowl 43. Asked g-ma to go to lunch but she declined. I do not think she wanted me to spend money on her. So I went down to visit and had Timmy and Holly come too. We stayed, ate brownies, and chatted for about 3 hours then headed to Mom's for her Superbowl party. She had a nice spread and is really amusing to watch her reaction to the commercials. I left after the 1st quarter to come home and spend time with the hubby and eat Jeff's delicious ribs and Terri's garlicy hummus. Somehow I managed to not fall asleep during the game, and the fourth quarter had me actually excited. The game changed leaders (2x) fast with the Steelers to beat the Cardinals. Sorry Cards, but you can be proud on how far you made it. To go from a recurring last place team to number 2 is surealy an accomplishment. 

2-2 Beck and I joined Planet Fitness in Peckville, which is a bit far for me but I know I will go if I have a buddy. And the buddy system has worked because we went 4 of the 5 weekdays this week. YAY!  She's a great gym buddy too. We are doing both cardio and weights. She hopes to eliminate 30lbs by June, and hell, so do I. This means I needed to weigh myself. Thankfully I have not gained any weight as I had feared since I moved back.  We both got the plan where we can bring unlimited guests, so we have a backup too. 
Could not sleep at night, so applied to 4 jobs. Haven't heard from any yet...... 

2-3 Rob and I ate at Kabuki Japanese. Decent sushi, better than Kyoto in Clarks S. but not as good as Phoenix. PA seems to put too much mayo in there spicy tuna/salmon, etc.  Service was not that great either, and the place was pretty empty. 
     Spent the night hanging at mom's. 

2-4 Grapped some cocoa and dessert with Melissa at Dunkin Donuts. Had some nice convo. with her. It's nice to get to know her better. 

2-6 After the gym met Terri and Jeff at Dino and Francesco's (their friday night food joint) for some grub.  I had a calzone and rice pudding, both pretty good. Terri got Chicken Picatta, which the sauce was superb - you could taste the right amount of lemon, butter, AND caper. 


Trying to study for the MCAT and not doing so well with it...... 
I am too much enjoying the laziness and galavanting.  Am I going to be able to "buckle down"

Took my brother to the Wilkes-barre Rock Climbing Gym on Sunday.  We had a good time together, and my brother enjoyed his first time climbing despite the WRCG sucks.  The walls are only about 20 feet high, hardly any routes are labled, the ones that are labeled may not be labeled correctly, they weren't very friendly, and they refused to show my brother how to belay, stating that their insurance does not cover that.  They were having a kids birthday party at the time and I said this place is full of kids and you can't teach how to belay?  Apparrently the two workers belay the kids.  How would you like to be a parent paying for a party and only two kids can climb at a time?  There were kids everywhere too.  I wonder if they switched from ATCs to Gri-gri's (no locking device to antilocking) if that would make a difference in the insurance. The PRG used gri-gris.  So I am torn.  On one hand I want to climb that is the only place to climb, BUT I don't want to give them my money.  I will probably go back a few times....  Since I do not know what I am climbing I can not mark my progression.  If I had the money and the skills I would make my own gym...  Bah! 

Monday night Rob and I went to Jimmy's to hang out and play some board  games.  We played Zombie Flux, a spin off of Flux, and a very interesting, fun game.  We all had a good time.  I'm glad my brothers and I get along better now that we are older.
Now what are comedians going to talk about for the next 8 years?

I have never watched an inaugeration before....in his speech President Obama gave me goosebumps 3x.  Here's to the future.  
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OBAMA: My fellow citizens:

I stand here today humbled by the task before us, grateful for the trust you have bestowed, mindful of the sacrifices borne by our ancestors. I thank President Bush for his service to our nation, as well as the generosity and cooperation he has shown throughout this transition.

Forty-four Americans have now taken the presidential oath. The words have been spoken during rising tides of prosperity and the still waters of peace. Yet, every so often the oath is taken amidst gathering clouds and raging storms. At these moments, America has carried on not simply because of the skill or vision of those in high office, but because we the people have remained faithful to the ideals of our forebears, and true to our founding documents.

So it has been. So it must be with this generation of Americans.

That we are in the midst of crisis is now well understood. Our nation is at war, against a far-reaching network of violence and hatred. Our economy is badly weakened, a consequence of greed and irresponsibility on the part of some, but also our collective failure to make hard choices and prepare the nation for a new age. Homes have been lost; jobs shed; businesses shuttered. Our health care is too costly; our schools fail too many; and each day brings further evidence that the ways we use energy strengthen our adversaries and threaten our planet.

These are the indicators of crisis, subject to data and statistics. Less measurable but no less profound is a sapping of confidence across our land — a nagging fear that America's decline is inevitable, and that the next generation must lower its sights.

Today I say to you that the challenges we face are real. They are serious and they are many. They will not be met easily or in a short span of time. But know this, America — they will be met.

On this day, we gather because we have chosen hope over fear, unity of purpose over conflict and discord.

On this day, we come to proclaim an end to the petty grievances and false promises, the recriminations and worn out dogmas, that for far too long have strangled our politics.

We remain a young nation, but in the words of scripture, the time has come to set aside childish things. The time has come to reaffirm our enduring spirit; to choose our better history; to carry forward that precious gift, that noble idea, passed on from generation to generation: the God-given promise that all are equal, all are free and all deserve a chance to pursue their full measure of happiness.

In reaffirming the greatness of our nation, we understand that greatness is never a given. It must be earned. Our journey has never been one of shortcuts or settling for less. It has not been the path for the faint-hearted — for those who prefer leisure over work, or seek only the pleasures of riches and fame. Rather, it has been the risk-takers, the doers, the makers of things — some celebrated but more often men and women obscure in their labor, who have carried us up the long, rugged path towards prosperity and freedom.

For us, they packed up their few worldly possessions and traveled across oceans in search of a new life.

For us, they toiled in sweatshops and settled the West; endured the lash of the whip and plowed the hard earth.

For us, they fought and died, in places like Concord and Gettysburg; Normandy and Khe Sahn.

Time and again these men and women struggled and sacrificed and worked till their hands were raw so that we might live a better life. They saw America as bigger than the sum of our individual ambitions; greater than all the differences of birth or wealth or faction.

This is the journey we continue today. We remain the most prosperous, powerful nation on Earth. Our workers are no less productive than when this crisis began. Our minds are no less inventive, our goods and services no less needed than they were last week or last month or last year. Our capacity remains undiminished. But our time of standing pat, of protecting narrow interests and putting off unpleasant decisions — that time has surely passed. Starting today, we must pick ourselves up, dust ourselves off, and begin again the work of remaking America.

For everywhere we look, there is work to be done. The state of the economy calls for action, bold and swift, and we will act — not only to create new jobs, but to lay a new foundation for growth. We will build the roads and bridges, the electric grids and digital lines that feed our commerce and bind us together. We will restore science to its rightful place, and wield technology's wonders to raise health care's quality and lower its cost. We will harness the sun and the winds and the soil to fuel our cars and run our factories. And we will transform our schools and colleges and universities to meet the demands of a new age. All this we can do. And all this we will do.

Now, there are some who question the scale of our ambitions — who suggest that our system cannot tolerate too many big plans. Their memories are short. For they have forgotten what this country has already done; what free men and women can achieve when imagination is joined to common purpose, and necessity to courage.

What the cynics fail to understand is that the ground has shifted beneath them — that the stale political arguments that have consumed us for so long no longer apply. The question we ask today is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works — whether it helps families find jobs at a decent wage, care they can afford, a retirement that is dignified. Where the answer is yes, we intend to move forward. Where the answer is no, programs will end. And those of us who manage the public's dollars will be held to account — to spend wisely, reform bad habits, and do our business in the light of day — because only then can we restore the vital trust between a people and their government.

Nor is the question before us whether the market is a force for good or ill. Its power to generate wealth and expand freedom is unmatched, but this crisis has reminded us that without a watchful eye, the market can spin out of control — and that a nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous. The success of our economy has always depended not just on the size of our gross domestic product, but on the reach of our prosperity; on our ability to extend opportunity to every willing heart — not out of charity, but because it is the surest route to our common good.

As for our common defense, we reject as false the choice between our safety and our ideals. Our founding fathers, faced with perils we can scarcely imagine, drafted a charter to assure the rule of law and the rights of man, a charter expanded by the blood of generations. Those ideals still light the world, and we will not give them up for expedience's sake. And so to all other peoples and governments who are watching today, from the grandest capitals to the small village where my father was born: know that America is a friend of each nation and every man, woman, and child who seeks a future of peace and dignity, and that we are ready to lead once more.

Recall that earlier generations faced down fascism and communism not just with missiles and tanks, but with sturdy alliances and enduring convictions. They understood that our power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please. Instead, they knew that our power grows through its prudent use; our security emanates from the justness of our cause, the force of our example, the tempering qualities of humility and restraint.

We are the keepers of this legacy. Guided by these principles once more, we can meet those new threats that demand even greater effort — even greater cooperation and understanding between nations. We will begin to responsibly leave Iraq to its people, and forge a hard-earned peace in Afghanistan. With old friends and former foes, we will work tirelessly to lessen the nuclear threat, and roll back the specter of a warming planet. We will not apologize for our way of life, nor will we waver in its defense, and for those who seek to advance their aims by inducing terror and slaughtering innocents, we say to you now that our spirit is stronger and cannot be broken; you cannot outlast us, and we will defeat you.

For we know that our patchwork heritage is a strength, not a weakness. We are a nation of Christians and Muslims, Jews and Hindus — and non-believers. We are shaped by every language and culture, drawn from every end of this Earth; and because we have tasted the bitter swill of civil war and segregation, and emerged from that dark chapter stronger and more united, we cannot help but believe that the old hatreds shall someday pass; that the lines of tribe shall soon dissolve; that as the world grows smaller, our common humanity shall reveal itself; and that America must play its role in ushering in a new era of peace.

To the Muslim world, we seek a new way forward, based on mutual interest and mutual respect. To those leaders around the globe who seek to sow conflict, or blame their society's ills on the West — know that your people will judge you on what you can build, not what you destroy. To those who cling to power through corruption and deceit and the silencing of dissent, know that you are on the wrong side of history; but that we will extend a hand if you are willing to unclench your fist.

To the people of poor nations, we pledge to work alongside you to make your farms flourish and let clean waters flow; to nourish starved bodies and feed hungry minds. And to those nations like ours that enjoy relative plenty, we say we can no longer afford indifference to suffering outside our borders; nor can we consume the world's resources without regard to effect. For the world has changed, and we must change with it.

As we consider the road that unfolds before us, we remember with humble gratitude those brave Americans who, at this very hour, patrol far-off deserts and distant mountains. They have something to tell us today, just as the fallen heroes who lie in Arlington whisper through the ages. We honor them not only because they are guardians of our liberty, but because they embody the spirit of service; a willingness to find meaning in something greater than themselves. And yet, at this moment — a moment that will define a generation — it is precisely this spirit that must inhabit us all.

For as much as government can do and must do, it is ultimately the faith and determination of the American people upon which this nation relies. It is the kindness to take in a stranger when the levees break, the selflessness of workers who would rather cut their hours than see a friend lose their job which sees us through our darkest hours. It is the firefighter's courage to storm a stairway filled with smoke, but also a parent's willingness to nurture a child, that finally decides our fate.

Our challenges may be new. The instruments with which we meet them may be new. But those values upon which our success depends — hard work and honesty, courage and fair play, tolerance and curiosity, loyalty and patriotism — these things are old. These things are true. They have been the quiet force of progress throughout our history. What is demanded then is a return to these truths. What is required of us now is a new era of responsibility — a recognition, on the part of every American, that we have duties to ourselves, our nation, and the world, duties that we do not grudgingly accept but rather seize gladly, firm in the knowledge that there is nothing so satisfying to the spirit, so defining of our character, than giving our all to a difficult task.

This is the price and the promise of citizenship.

This is the source of our confidence — the knowledge that God calls on us to shape an uncertain destiny.

This is the meaning of our liberty and our creed — why men and women and children of every race and every faith can join in celebration across this magnificent mall, and why a man whose father less than sixty years ago might not have been served at a local restaurant can now stand before you to take a most sacred oath.

So let us mark this day with remembrance, of who we are and how far we have traveled. In the year of America's birth, in the coldest of months, a small band of patriots huddled by dying campfires on the shores of an icy river. The capital was abandoned. The enemy was advancing. The snow was stained with blood. At a moment when the outcome of our revolution was most in doubt, the father of our nation ordered these words be read to the people:

"Let it be told to the future world ... that in the depth of winter, when nothing but hope and virtue could survive...that the city and the country, alarmed at one common danger, came forth to meet (it)."

America, in the face of our common dangers, in this winter of our hardship, let us remember these timeless words. With hope and virtue, let us brave once more the icy currents, and endure what storms may come. Let it be said by our children's children that when we were tested we refused to let this journey end, that we did not turn back nor did we falter; and with eyes fixed on the horizon and God's grace upon us, we carried forth that great gift of freedom and delivered it safely to future generations.

I bought this book – What Matters, which is a photo journal and written blurbs about global warming, environmental degradation, AIDS, genocide in Darfur, the global jihad, and the inequitable distribution of global wealth, among other challenges the world faces – after much deliberation.  I knew if I bought it the images would make me angry (how can such a modern world continue to let these issues exist, and furthermore grow?) yet hopeless in the fact that they is nothing I could do, and nothing would ever change.  Well the editor makes an excellent point in the intro “we actually did abolish slavery and child labor in the US, we abolished the apartheid in South Africa; we defeated the Nazis; we pulled out of Vietnam; and Minamata Bay was eventually cleaned up.  As the saying goes, ‘All great social change seems impossible until it is inevitable.’  This does revive some of my hope.  However,  challenges this great are going to need all the earth’s country’s to ban together….and maybe we are a little….but I don’t think we are enough.  The book also offers some resources on things we/I can do to take action and help.  I will have to look carefully at that. Hopefully there is more in there than the standard use less electricity/water, recycle, etc.  The little man can help in these respects, but only a little – Big business is truly were changes need to be made in that area.  Not that the “little man” should cease all efforts.

The shortcake was just heavenly.   I have never liked the shortcake from stores, but when you make it yourself, Wow.  I took a picture but since I use Rob's parents pc now I do not know if I will ever upload stuff on here, at least for a while. 

Dad did not bail. =)  It was nice to go out with him. Hitcock's movie, 39 steps, was ok.  A Betty Boop cartoon, where she is Cinderella, was played before the movie. She was a lot less curvy than I remember, but maybe they toned the curves down a bit since Cinderella is traditionally not a hooch.  The Vintage "theater" was a small room off of the old Ritz theater.  The Ritz in its prime I am sure was marvelous, but I remember it as a dollar of two dollar semi-run down movie place.  I think now it's a blues cafe?  In Vintage a few chairs were lined up and a projector played (digital) movies on the wall.  It was cute I guess, (and I might try it out again next week because they are playing a romance from the 40s, which I think might be interesting) but you could buy or rent the DVD and watch it at home on a much more comfortable chair.  

Afterwords we went to Chick's Diner - a real diner, perhaps even quintesstential? - and ate the best open face roast beef sandwich I have ever had.  The mashed potatoes were awesome - that helped a bit.  I laughed a bit at their placemats because amid the advertisements for local businesses, Chick's proclaims to be the Scranton Landmark.  I just thought it a bit odd, but I guess I'll have to ask around.  When I think Scranton, I don't think Chick's (though after that meal maybe I should).  Instead, I think trains and coal, and memories. 

Then I went and watched TV with Dad for an hour before heading home.  It was nice to get some one on one time with him. That does not happen too often. I learned he really likes stand-up comedy because I was telling him about Wise Crackers last night.  It looks like  we may have more in common than I thought.

A buck was trying to steal my parking space.   As I pulled into the driveway, a 6-pointer stared at me.  Even if I had been camera ready, I think it would be too dark to get a good shot.  Pretty cool though.  It’s 12:43am, I got home about 15 minutes ago.  It’s -6oF outside, so cold that when you try to heat your car up you need to start it an hour before you want to use it, lol.  I joined a NEPA hiking group and was supposed to go on my first hike with them tomorrow, but it was cancelled because temps are supposed to be a high of 5oF. Lovely.   So instead I plan to make homemade strawberry shortcake and catch an Alfred Hitchcock flick at the grand opening of Scranton’s Vintage Theater with my Dad….or Candace if Dad bails on me.

Tonight I celebrated Becky’s birthday.  Meeting at her house we (Beck, Jer, and me) stopped for dessert at good ole Burger King….I should have been smart and made her favorite spice cake – Darn!  But the Butterfinger mousse pie was pretty good.  We thought about going somewhere fancy for dessert but the time got away from us as we had to be at Wise Crackers – a comedy club in the Clarion Hotel – at 8:30pm to meet her two friends Erin and Luke for the 9pm show.  It kinda fit the day because I was watching stand-up all day on Comedy Central – GO STAND-UP MONTH!  I had a good time. The MC and the first guy weren’t so great, but the last two guys were pretty funny.  The headliner…..Tim Young, I guess has been on Last Comic Standing and Comedy Central.  I was glad Becky picked the event, not me, because all of the comedians were being pretty vulgar, and I was a little embarrassed because I did not know how Beck and Jer would take the jokes.  They seemed to flow with it though.  Both me and Luke won the raffle of which the prizes were one free ticket each to come back next week.  So I think it will be us 5 again, lol.  I’m going to see if I can find a warm bed to crawl into now, think I’ll make some hot cocoa first.

Ah, almost forgot....one major difference between Phoenix and here, is the lack of flatness for miles and miles.  The hills and mountains here make it difficult to exist on a gris system, so well there isn't one. Which I used to think was great, but Becky lives in Carbondale, which on a land map looks to be almost a straight shot East of Dalton; one would think 20 minutes by car.  But thanks to mountains, I have to go southeast than northeast in a V type shape - 40 minutes without traffic and red lights. It toik me about 50min to get there.

One cool thing about the drive home is that though I am on a main highway, it's so dark and unpopulated that it feels like the middle of nowhere. It was nice to listen to some jazz, cruising down the highway, going over hills so that there are trees on one side and the twinkling of "city" lights below.

I think I have done quite a bit this last week.  Let’s see if I can remember it all.

Today was a relaxing day, though a bit stressful at the end because it turned to waiting.   We were projected to get 8-12 inches of snow, so I decided I was not going to venture out at all.  We had 5 inches at 4pm. Its 1:27am now. I have no idea how much snow we got but it’s sleeting now.  Rob is spending the night at his buddy’s because it was his day to role play and the roads are bad.  (I wonder if I will have a hard time sleeping without him.) So I spent my time calling every person in my cell phone contact list (aside from doctors and restaurants).  I worked my way through it alphabetically having some great conversations and some mundane ones, but all were long.   I also started and finished a book – fiction – that started terrible but ended well.  If it had continued as it had started I would have never finished it. Still I don’t think I would recommend it to anyone.

I saw some wonderful things over the past week.  Today there were 5 deer running across the road, a few days ago there were 4 female turkeys in the yard, I found a live lady bug in the house (which I think country people find as a nuisance because that can make infestations, but I always think of good luck because of what my mom told me as a child), and I think that last one…hope I did not forget any was one day it was softly flurrying and I saw a black horse standing away from his barn back covered in snow, contently eating grass.  That horse was truly beautiful.

Sunday – Robs g-parents

Tuesday – Becky Shopping then snow (horse day)

Wednesday – Russian Christmas

Thursday - recovery and mom’s

Friday movie with mom and hospital; TGIF’s

Sunday the Zimmerman’s made their annual Holiday trek down to Harrisburg to visit Rob’s grandparents and aunts and uncles from Jeff’s side.  I was dreading sitting in the car, but actually ended up sleeping through most of the ride. YES!  It was nice to see Grammie Bev. Pappi Bob, Aunt Jackie, Uncle Pete, Uncle Mike, and Ian again.  There are a good bunch of people.  I am surprised that his family gets me Christmas presents, even family that I only met at the wedding (like on X-mas eve).  They really make me feel welcome in the family.  There was football watching and lots of food eating. Then the drive home, where I managed to sleep again.

I cannot remember what I did Monday – eep!

Tuesday, Beckers picked me up in Clarks Summit and we went to be girlie at the mall.  We bought fancy panties, shoes, and purses. It can’t get much girlier than that. Oh wait; we had salads for lunch too. =)  Everyone knows I hate shopping but it was one of the most fun times shopping that I have had, and I am fighting my inner girl less and less as time goes on….maybe even embracing it a little, and learning to balance it more.   I’m not afraid of it anymore.

Wednesday Good ole Chris invited me to Russian Christmas.  I missed the feasting but had plenty of time for the liquid festivities.  Like any good NEPAer in winter, the beer was kept on the porch to ensure proper temperatures for ultimate refreshment.  I started with beer, but after the Goopies came (people from the Russian Orthodox Church with painted faces, white pants stuffed with hay, and axes (fake) to persuade you to donate monies into their collection cans for the church) and sang Christmas carols in Russian, the Russian drinking songs ensued.   I learned the hard way that they is a certain point in a RD song where you are supposed to drink (Glug, glug, glug – the English portion yay!) and if you drink before this, you have to drink again.  (I guess they used to pour drinks on offenders until they realized it was alcohol abuse).   It was a grand ole time and I was a little saddened that it took me all for these years to actually go to one….but hey there is always next year.  

Thursday – of course with any heavy night of drinking comes the next excruciating day of recovery, full of headaches, stomach aches, and chances to see if that possible hunger pain really wants crackers or just a visit to the restroom.  Nothing but fun here.  Later that night I went to hang out with mom, chicken soup in tow.  She took Thurs. and Friday off because she got Larangitis, so I promised we go to the movies Friday, when we went to see The Curious Case of Benjamin Button.   Our night was cut short when visited Terri in the hospital.  She was having chest pains, which thankfully turned out to be only muscle pain from all the ice chopping she had been doing. Whew. Way to worry a girl.  We had some good jokes with her nurses about eating fried foods and bacon on the cardio ward (Jeff had gotten Arby’s – fried stuff for him, turkey Rueben for her) and having to go buy her underwear because she was not wearing any….apparently Jeff was not either. Glad I am not the only one that goes commando.  Though I have been sporting some cotton briefs since the move.   After visiting hours, I met up with Rob and his buddies at TGIFS for some grub and stories about adolescent Rob.  Hehe.

No really, I am bored and waiting for the hubby.  Also I noticed in reading other people's lists that I have completed many of the things that they want to do. cool.  I guess I will try to update this on here every 6 months. These are more like smaller life directional goals...I don't know sometimes I think these things are stupid, other times I just can't help myself.

Wow.   So I know there is no way this can continue happening….I mean nothing remains happy/perfectly comfortable (or whatever word I am looking for) forever, right?  I had another great night out with friends.  Maybe it is because it is my first long hang out with these people in many many years, or maybe it’s because I went in with low expectations…dunno, but it’s great and I am going to hang on to it for as long as I can.

The day started with some nice hang out time with the in laws.  They were making lasagna for our trip down to visit Rob’s grandparents and aunts and uncles tomorrow (can’t wait to eat it, smells & looks so good).  Then I helped Jeff (by helping measure and holding wood) put some molding in the back room that they are refinishing to turn into a shower room, etc. for when they get old and can’t get up the stairs anymore.

Luckily after that I had a project of seeding the Chia pet (elephant) that Becky gave me for X-mas.  =)  I just love fun little projects.

Then I picked up Candace and we took the 40 min trek to Wilkes Barre to the Barnes and Noble, so I could use my gift card from Rob’s Uncle Dogface (Jimmy) and Aunt Patty gave me for X-mas.  It was awful nice of them to get me a present.   So I not only got a NEPA hiking guide and that photo-journal book I thought about getting in Phoenix (but didn’t because I thought pics of third world countries would just piss me off like national geographic does --- and it was 50% off now) but I also got to have heartfelt conversations with my long time buddy.  I do not think I have had one on one time with her in close to 10 years.  She’s such a social butterfly (to put it lightly  =)  ), which is of course a great thing and part of her special flavor.  I just wish things were going better for her.  She does not deserve the shit she has been going through.

Yesterday was both a good and bad day. 

It was Nancy's birthday - YAY! So we went to see Mark Zubia do his acoustic set at Jalapeno Inferno.  She really enjoys his music and goes to every gig she can. We drank martinis, and I got him to sing happy birthday to her. Hehe. That was cool.  Near the end we were the only ones there, so it turned into our own little request line, lol.  I think Nancy got to request six songs.  =)

Then I can home and was hanging out with Rob.  He went to go feed Harvey our blue, crazy beta that we have had for almost 2 1/2 years....and he was dead. I loved that crazy little guy, always so excited to see me, zooming around his bowl, attacking the glass marbles, making random noises all the time.  I cried a little.  He was such a great fish. We buried him outside with a seashell that was by his bowl. Rob thought it would be nice to put something with him that he saw everyday. 

I was going to cart him across the country back to PA in a big gulp cup.....

So months back when gas hit $4.09, I thought it would never go back down. And if it did somehow manage to go down I certainly did not think I would ever see it below $2.00 again. 

Well, I just paid $1.99.  =)

Hopefully the price will continue to drop or stay the same through January, so Rob and I do not have to use all of our wedding money on gas when moving back across the country. Ah, the excitement!

Darkness has been falling much earlier. At about 5:20pm every day the sun is in the late stages of setting.   Rather depressing. Depressing because human's should not spend the sunlight hours huddled in caves (offices). Sigh. Mondernity. 


I did see two rather pretty sunsets this week, though I was driving home, so I could not stop to enjoy them.  They were very different.

I wonder if my mind could vividly recall a sunset, or really anything for that matter if I were to go blind.

Thousands to protest passage of state same-sex marriage bans in cities across the U.S. Nov. 15. Expect transportation disruptions.

The locations affected by this alert are Chicago, Ill., Atlanta, Ga., Baltimore, Md., Boston, Mass., Denver, Colo., Detroit, Mich., Houston, Texas, Los Angeles, Calif., Miami, Fla., Minneapolis, Minn., New York City, N.Y., Oakland, Calif., Philadelphia, Pa., Phoenix, Ariz., Sacramento, Calif., San Diego, Calif., San Francisco, Calif., San Jose, Calif., St Louis, Mo., Washington D.C., Monterey, Calif..
This alert began 14 Nov 2008 22:11 GMT and is scheduled to expire 15 Nov 2008 23:59 GMT.

 - Event: Join the Impact protests
 - Date: Nov. 15
 - Location: Urban areas across the U.S.
 - Impact: Traffic disruptions
Summary
Thousands of people will participate in a nationwide protest movement against the passage of same-sex marriage bans in Arizona, California and Florida. Rallies have been planned in hundreds of cities, the largest of which will occur in:

 - Phoenix, Ariz.: 200 W. Washington St.
 - Los Angeles, Calif.: outside City Hall at 200 N. Spring St.
 - San Diego, Calif.: intersection of 6th Avenue and Upas Street
 - San Francisco, Calif.: outside City Hall at 1 Dr. Carlton B. Goodlett Pl.

 - Baltimore, Md.: 100 Holliday St.

<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal">October 2008 NG notes:</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->All baseballs used in the Major Leagues are rubbed in special mud from top secret spots before they are used to help players grip them.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->Rats are being used to sniff out land mines. They are better to use than dogs because they don’t set off the mines and are easy to feed and breed.<span style="">  </span>Cool, eh?</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->Modern man is not a descendant of Neanderthals.<span style="">  </span>These people lived in northern “<st1:place w:st="on">Eurasia</st1:place>” and had red hair.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->European Bee Eaters (birds) are breathtakingly beautiful!<span style="">  </span>There bodies are a striking bright teal with a bright yellow throat and brown head and wings.<span style="">  </span>Of course they eat bees (and other insects), and know how to remove the stingers.<span style="">   </span>To mate males must catch the female a bug then dance around with it before knocking it out. If the female eats it and likes it, the male is in, lol.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->A dog named <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:city w:st="on">Fargo</st1:city></st1:place>, a Rottweiler, is the world’s first whale poop sniffing dog.<span style="">   </span>He could pick up a scent from up to a mile off<span style="">  </span>and alerts the boat crew of the direction to go with a wag of his tail.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]-->National Hiking Trials are upkept by volunteers. There is a map of all the trails in this issue. I never knew there was so many!<span style="">  </span>It makes me want to hike ‘em.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in; text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style="">-<span style="font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">          </span></span><!--[endif]--><st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region w:st="on">India</st1:country-region></st1:place> is diligently working on a <st1:street w:st="on"><st1:address w:st="on">National   Highway</st1:address></st1:street> – the Golden Quadrilateral – to connect all 4 quadrants of the country. (It’s 3633 miles.)<span style="">  </span>It will be a very big loop, and the sacred cows are not stopped from holding up traffic. Every night, Indians line up in a Hindu temple at <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:city w:st="on">Bangalore</st1:city></st1:place> to have their vehicles blessed by a Hindu priest in the name of god Lord Ganesh before they will drive them. Some Indian Historians are calling this the birth of “<st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region w:st="on">India</st1:country-region></st1:place> after Gandhi”, and the new highway has both good and bad implications for Indians.<span style="">  </span>There will be new jobs in the cities because as demand for cars increases, the current factories will need more workers and other small businesses (i.e., windshield suppliers, etc.) will open; however, the government is taking land from farmers, destroying their livelihoods, to build the road.<span style="">  </span>These farmers do hold protests, especially when they are not receiving compensation for their land.<span style="">  </span>Many of the farmers not knowing what else to do are resorting to suicide! (not kidding).<span style="">  </span>Other farmers are benefiting from the road as it goes by them not through them connecting them to bigger cities where they get more of a profit for their crops, and cities/jobs that used to be 3 hrs away are now 45min on the hwy (doing less then 30mi/h). Overall the road has caused the poverty level drop and the middle class to swell – it’s just terrible that still many people are being left behind…….</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 0.5in;">Why are there no other alternatives being offered for the farmers that have to give up everything, especially since <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region w:st="on">India</st1:country-region></st1:place> seems to be greatly benefiting.</p></meta></meta></meta></meta>

Two letters came to me in the mail today (11/6) - one from grandma and the other from my Uncle Joey.  I love getting letters.  There is just something so wonderful and special about it…maybe because they let you know that you’re wonderful and special because someone took the time to write them.  I’ll miss it when I move back.   In the old days mail consisted of importance and love, but now it’s mainly junk. So sad.

 

Had a wonderful day with my lover muffin today. =)  I was naughty and skipped cell bio to stay in bed with him where we cuddled til noon. Then we went for lunch and had one of those simple but special times that is filled with such happiness and love, where you can feel the true connection.   It’s pretty indescribable, but I am sure anyone that has had moments like this knows what I am talking about.

 

It was just so…..everything. =)

 

It really put my soul at ease and made me feel warm and whole inside.

 

He dropped me at class and went off to work. I cleaned then went to dinner with Jennifer. We had a good time catching up.  There is so much turmoil in her life I don’t know how she deals with it, but I think she has the strength to get through.

 

Now I am waiting for the boys to call for their ride home as they as bonding over large quantities of high alcohol beer.  Some people wonder why I would stay up for that and not make them figure out a way home….I mean come on, it’s love.  Being there for each other is of the utmost importance (though I am sleepy), lol.
Went climbing again last night.  Now the fleshy side of my elbow joint is sore.   That is like the worst place!

The next president of the United States of America is Barack Hussein Obama.

The road ahead will be long, but it will also be full of hope.

Let's do this!



What a great speech.  It brought tears to my eyes.


Not so great turn outs on the election here in AZ included the passing of a proposition against gay marriage.
::sigh:: I really do not see why people are so afraid of this....

Voters approve proposal to ban gay marriage

by Mary Jo Pitzl - Nov. 5, 2008 12:00 AM
The Arizona Republic

The second time around proved the charm, as Arizona voters approved a constitutional amendment that bans same-sex marriage.

Proposition 102 proposed a 20-word amendment to the state Constitution to define marriage as between one man and one woman. It's an attempt to do what backers couldn't do in 2006: ensure that Arizona's existing law banning same-sex marriages will not be overturned by a judge.

"Prop. 102's victory shows that a simple and timeless value like marriage unites people of all ethnic, religious and political backgrounds," said Cathi Herrod, president of the Center for Arizona Policy, which lobbied heavily to get lawmakers to refer the matter to the ballot. In 2006, Arizona voters rejected a same-sex marriage amendment, making it the only state ever to turn down such a ban. However, that measure included a provision that would have barred state and local governments from offering domestic-partner benefits to their employees, and many felt that doomed the measure two years ago.

The marriage amendment returned to the political arena this year after a contentious debate in the state Senate that mirrored the passions the marriage issue creates in society.

Its immediate effect is no change: Same-sex marriage already is against the law in Arizona and the ban has been upheld by the courts.

But proponents, many of them coming from Arizona's churches, argued that the constitutional amendment is needed to guard against a potential legal turnabout.

A similar ban passed in Florida and appeared to be winning in California.

Today we make history.   I hope.

<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal">Went climbing both weekends.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Last weekend was awesome.<span style="">  </span>I was flying up the routes with ease.<span style="">  </span>Did a 5.7, 5.8, 5.8, 5.8, 5.8, then got tired and struggled through two 5.7s and a 5.6.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Yesterday I was so tired and did not want to go but now am very glad I went.<span style="">  </span>5.7, 5.8, 5.7, 5.8, 5.7, 5.6.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">I need to find a way to increase my strength endurance because the last climbs feel terrible</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">My arms are absolutely killing me today, even when I don’t move them! <span style=""> </span>They feel like bricks hanging off of my body.<span style="">   </span>Even typing hurts.</p>

<![endif]--><p class="MsoNormal">Took a Professional Rescuer CPR and First Aid Class over the weekend.</p><p class="MsoNormal">I was not impressed by the first aid part at all.<span>  </span>That part all we did was watch a video for about an hour and take a short multiple choice test.<span>   </span>I have a manual, but I thought they were going to teach me more.</p><p class="MsoNormal">I did learn a few choice tidbits, such as how to recognize of someone is having a stroke.<span>  </span>It has the acronym FAST for Face (make them smile, if they can’t do it or one side is droopy they might be having a stroke), Arm (have them lift both of there arms in front of them and then upwards to see if they can both be lifted the same), Speech (have the person say a simple sentence) Time (tell 911 what time the symptoms started to appear). From working in the ER last semester I learned that timing in getting people treatment for a stroke is very important, and damage can reduced if treatment is given within an hour.<span>  </span>So knowing someone is having a stroke and being able to tell 911 that is quite awesome.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">The CPR class was a lot more in depth that the training I received at PCH (Phoenix Children’s Hospital) – I <span> </span>guess there is many varying CPR classes out there that teach things slightly differently. One would think that it should be universal.<span>  </span>Well the actual CPR part was pretty much the same…but there was an additional breathing part, which we were told that CPR does not work if air can’t enter the body (the person choked on something) SO they taught us techniques for both conscious and unconscious choking.<span>   </span>I would think this info to be beneficial for all CPR classes. <span>  </span>Plus I do think both of my classes were certified by the American Red Cross.<span>  </span>I also learned that CPR certs are only good for one year now, not 2 as my previous one was.</p><br />After class on Saturday I was hungry, so decided to walk the few blocks to a little family restaurant that serves healthy and delicious meals called Plaid. Well....it looks like they have been closed for a while = bummer. But my nose picked up on some wafting deliciousness from around the corner and I found a tiny run down Indo-Pakistani place (that had a bunch of chicken feathers blowing acorss the ground outside...could it be that fresh?!)  They were serving buffet style. The food was good (lots of chicken) albeit a tiny bit cold since I had been scraping up the last of everything. I was the only white person in there and nearly the only female, yet I did not feel weird.  As I was paying the women asked me if it was too spicy for me....it was not, but upon her asking I realized that it was a lot spicier than I usually have.  I wish their were more ethnic food places that did not Americanize their cuisine....of course if they did that then they might not get as much business (Ah, there's the rub, right Billy?)<br />

After reading NG (yes, here we go again), I sent this to everyone in my e-mail address book.  O boi, I'm becoming one of those people. 

Hi All, 

Do not buy palm oil or anything made from it. Borneo's biodiversity and its people are being destroyed from plan oil's  high global demands because forest is cleared for plantations.  Over 8 million acres of Borneo (that's the size of switzerland!) has been cleared so far. We are putting 44 species of mammals, 74 species of birds, 91 species of retiles, 114 species of ampjibians, 160 species of fish, and 155 species fo trees that can NOT be found anywhere else in the world in danger of extinction. 

Let's stop destroying our planet. 

KZ

<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal">Thesis defense went swimmingly. The presentation was about 18 minutes long. <br /><br />Had a great time with Teresa tonight.<span style="">  </span>She told me about 80 million times “Congratualtions” on the finishing of my thesis.<span style="">  </span>We were going to go to a haunted house, but in net surfing today I discovered none of they are open on Mondays or Tuesdays. =(<span style="">  </span>So, we went to a El Salvadorean restaurant (Salvadoreno Restaurant) that I had been wanting to try for a long time.<span style="">  </span>Everything was pretty excellent except for the horchata – some type of drink, that we ordered because Teresa had “it” before and said it was really good. BUT it was really traditional (not like she had it, but not sure how its different), so it tasted…..well….like vomit. It tasted good in your mouth, kinda milky, but the second you swallow it – Whoahoho.<span style="">  </span>It definitely had a strong…er….aftertaste.<span style="">  </span>We both were kinda making faces at each other and we knew what it tasted like but we weren’t saying it – until we got into the parking lot. Teresa ordered some shrimp ceviche, which was very fresh and had a spiciness that snuck up on you, very very good. I got a traditional scrambled egg breakfast, that I think had sausage in it. It came with blackened rice, some goat cheese (that reminded me of <st1:country-region w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Honduras</st1:place></st1:country-region>), tortillas, and a black bean dip. It was very greasy, but also very tasty. Then of course you can’t go to a Salvaldorean restaurant and not eat some pupusas. We tried the pork and cheese ones, which were well worth the overfull feeling at the end of the meal.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">They were selling “I love pupusas” bumper stickers for a dollar, so thinking it was absolutely cute and funny I bought one.<span style="">  </span>the nice lady showed me there is a 1 dollar off coupon on the back that I can use after I put it on my car….well I’m not really going to put it on my car, oh and they have a…Myspace? (myspace.com/restaurante_saladoreno)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">I just really had a great time at dinner – it was one of those just unexplainably happy and perfect times, easygoing, full of laughs and smiles.<span style="">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Teresa really is such a great friends, and a wonderful person.<span style="">  </span>If only it were proper to send Peter a thank you card for standing me up the night I met her. Ah, well.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Speaking of good food there is always the thought that the food id good when you are at a ethinic restaurant and you look around and notice that you are the only white people in the place…. may be stereotypical but is true.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">We also learned today not to stand in the parking lot of a strip mall that has a check cashing place, a family dollar, a big lots, and a pawn shop. This guy on a bike came up, did not speak much English at all. We learned he was trying to sell up some sort of service, we said no, but he didn’t listen, and he started washing Teresa’s headlights. We didn’t know what to do and were dicussing how much we should give him. He kept saying something about how new it looks and one is free….ah we got it make the one look awesome – which he did , so he can charge for the other one. Not a bad idea my friend. He wanted 20 bucks to do the other one. We pretended like we only had 4 dollars, so he took that, left his bike and started walking towards the pawn shop.<span style="">  </span>We were like Whhhhaaat? but used the opportunity to bail it the hell outta there.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p>

Thesis advisor made me get up ASS early to go to the Buddy Walk. We set up a table to sign up participants for our lab.  They had free food (breakfast and lunch), free games, free face painting and entertainment. The walk was slow and once around the park.  They had cheerleaders set-up all around it to give high foves and encourage,ment.  It was cool to interact with kids and babies with DS because I usually only see adults with DS. Overall I thought it was a really nice day and nicely set up.  Our booth was next to an artist with DS, and I bought some of her art. Megan and I got our faces painted like spiderman.  Why not?

Volunteer with Agua Muisne, a non-profit organization dedicated to providing rural Ecuadorian communities with sustainable and safe water solutions. Agua Muisne has been working for two years in Ecuador researching water conditions, educating the local population about the health risks of contaminated water, and constructing water treatment systems. In the summer of 2007 we constructed our first water treatment system in the southwestern county of Muisne, which has since been providing water for 200 families a day. We are continuing to build water treatment systems in rural towns and villages where we are the sole provider of safe drinking water for thousands of people. Our mission focuses on dramatically improving the health and economic prosperity of the Ecuadorian populations we serve.

 

What do Volunteers do?

Agua Muisne is seeking highly motivated and entrepreneurial college students to research public health problems related to unsafe drinking water, work with communities to initiate and organize the construction of water treatment systems, and to lead campaigns to educate the local population about safe drinking water and good hygiene. This is an excellent opportunity for passionate Spanish-speaking students to experience first-hand how they can improve the lives of people living in the Developing World. 

 

For more information or to apply go to www.waterecuador.org.

Friday met Greg at Pranksters for trivia and some good ole cheap flat beer. It was fun. =)

Saturday I talked him and Alex into going to the 7th Annual KoKoPelli Krush at the KoKoPelli Winery in Chandler. They had wine tasting (6 tastes for 10 bucks)and a grape crushing contest for teams of two. Alex and I won the kids division,(two tickets to the Narnia exposition at the AZ Science Center; I let her have both of them)crushing 2.53lbs of juice - which may not have been fair since I was the one crushing - she ran me the grapes and then helped crush...so I felt a little bad (we pummeled them) but there were only 2 other kids teams. We thought we were in the adult crush because we paid the adult price (could win a trip to Hawaii), so we ended up getting a free crush in the adults section - which worked out nicely because Teresa showed up, so her and Greg got to crush. =) Crushing was so much fun - truly it made my day, lol. At first you think nothing is happening but after about a minute the juice has risen to above your feet. It is a very fun and sticky experience. Their wines weren't too bad - they had a very wide selection to choose from and some type of wine/champagne mix slushie - blue and very nice for a hot day.
There was one (white)wine that Teresa tried called Rhineland or something like that, which the pourer likened to Reisling, that was very interesting. But I do not think it was anywhere close to the Reez. It had a very smoky flavor and kinda tasted like Bar-B-Q, which is great if you are BBQing and wanting/expecting that type of thing, but when you are expecting a nice sweet refreshing white you are like uh, er, um, lol. 
That night Rob and I went to see W. It made me actually feel a little sympathy for the guy.

Rob took Sunday off of work, so we went to Chompie's for breakfast (Jewish & bagel place - very popular).  I tried the cheese blintzes and learned that blinztes really aren't  my thing - too sweet. Then we were off to the shooting range, then to see Max Payne, which entertained me, but not Rob. I didn't think it was great but I didn't hate myself for watching it. I think Rob did, but I went in with super low expectations. Later, we chilled out, ate some lo mein from Pei Wei and watched Pet Sematary.
It was very very nice to see him, since we haven't gotten much time together  because of campaign season, and it made me pretty giddy throughout the day.

All in all it was an enjoyable weekend. 

This morning (7:30am Argh!) was back to the bump and grind of Thesis writing. The Prof and I finished up the manuscript and sent it off to the other readers. It's decent but will need to be beefed up a bit for publishing, BUT the prof is pretty certain it will be published!  YAY!
So I need to have a presentation started by Wednesday...and defense is on Monday!  Wow, how the time flies!

I guess I shouldn't worry so much about forgetting "current events", after all don't we forget our own life events. Isn't that why people journal, blog, take photos?

Duh. AHA! Whatever.
